## Task 1 — Install kubectl

### Why

`kubectl` is the command-line interface for Kubernetes. Every operation — creating pods, checking logs, scaling deployments, applying manifests — goes through `kubectl`. Without it, you cannot communicate with any Kubernetes cluster, whether local (Minikube) or cloud (EKS, GKE).

### How It Was Done

The kubectl binary was installed from the official Kubernetes apt repository. The steps add the signing key, register the repository, and then install the package through apt.

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y apt-transport-https ca-certificates curl

curl -fsSL https://pkgs.k8s.io/core:/stable:/v1.34/deb/Release.key \
  | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/kubernetes-apt-keyring.gpg

echo 'deb [signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/kubernetes-apt-keyring.gpg] \
  https://pkgs.k8s.io/core:/stable:/v1.34/deb/ /' \
  | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/kubernetes.list

sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y kubectl
```

### Verification

```bash
kubectl version --client
```

Expected output confirms the kubectl binary version and that it is ready to connect to a cluster.

### Screenshot

