## Task 2 — Install Minikube

### Why

Minikube creates a single-node Kubernetes cluster on your local machine using Docker as the underlying driver. It is the standard tool for learning Kubernetes locally without needing cloud infrastructure or multiple physical machines. The entire control plane and worker node run inside one Docker container or VM on your machine.

### How It Was Done

The Minikube binary was downloaded directly from the official Google storage URL and installed as a system binary.

```bash
curl -LO https://storage.googleapis.com/minikube/releases/latest/minikube-linux-amd64
sudo install minikube-linux-amd64 /usr/local/bin/minikube
```

### Verification

```bash
minikube version
```

### Screenshot

> **[SCREENSHOT — minikube version output]**

---

## Task 3 — Start a Local Kubernetes Cluster

### Why

Running `minikube start` boots the entire Kubernetes control plane (API server, scheduler, controller manager, etcd) and a worker node inside a Docker container on your machine. Until the cluster is started, `kubectl` has no cluster to connect to and all commands will fail.

The `--driver=docker` flag tells Minikube to use Docker containers to simulate nodes rather than creating a separate virtual machine. This is faster and works well inside WSL.

### How It Was Done

```bash
minikube start --driver=docker
```

Minikube downloaded the required Kubernetes images, started the container, and configured `kubectl` to point to the new local cluster automatically.

### Verification

```bash
kubectl get nodes
```

Expected output shows one node with status `Ready`. This confirms the cluster is running and `kubectl` is connected to it.

```
NAME       STATUS   ROLES           AGE   VERSION
minikube   Ready    control-plane   1m    v1.34.x
```

### Screenshot

> **[SCREENSHOT — minikube start output showing successful startup]**

> **[SCREENSHOT — kubectl get nodes output showing minikube node as Ready]**

