## Task 5 — Write and Apply a Deployment YAML

### Why

A Deployment is the standard way to run applications in Kubernetes. It does not just start one container — it manages a set of identical pods (replicas) and continuously ensures the desired number is always running. If a pod crashes, the Deployment controller automatically creates a new one. If you want to update the application, the Deployment handles rolling updates one pod at a time with no downtime.

Writing the YAML manually is important because it teaches you what each field means, rather than just running auto-generated commands.

### How It Was Done

The `deployment.yaml` file was created in the week6 directory:

```bash
cat > deployment.yaml <<'EOF'
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: devops-web
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: devops-web
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: devops-web
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: devops-web
          image: nginx:alpine
          ports:
            - containerPort: 80
EOF
```

**Field-by-field explanation:**

| Field | Value | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| `apiVersion` | `apps/v1` | Which Kubernetes API group handles Deployments |
| `kind` | `Deployment` | The type of resource being created |
| `metadata.name` | `devops-web` | The name of this Deployment |
| `spec.replicas` | `2` | Always keep 2 pods running |
| `selector.matchLabels` | `app: devops-web` | The Deployment manages pods with this label |
| `template.metadata.labels` | `app: devops-web` | Every pod created will carry this label |
| `containers.image` | `nginx:alpine` | The Docker image to run inside each pod |
| `containerPort` | `80` | The port the application listens on inside the container |

The manifest was then applied to the cluster:

```bash
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
```

### Verification

```bash
kubectl get deployments
kubectl get pods
```

Expected output:

```
NAME        READY   UP-TO-DATE   AVAILABLE   AGE
devops-web  2/2     2            2           30s
```

```
NAME                          READY   STATUS    RESTARTS   AGE
devops-web-6d7f9c8b5d-abc12   1/1     Running   0          30s
devops-web-6d7f9c8b5d-def34   1/1     Running   0          30s
```

Two pods are running because `replicas: 2` was set in the manifest.

### Screenshot

> **[SCREENSHOT — kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml output]**

> **[SCREENSHOT — kubectl get deployments showing READY 2/2]**

> **[SCREENSHOT — kubectl get pods showing both pods in Running state]**

