## Learning Reflection

This week demonstrated how Kubernetes moves beyond individual containers. The core insight is the **reconciliation loop**: Kubernetes constantly compares the desired state (defined in YAML) with the actual state (running pods) and takes action to close the gap. This is why deleting a pod does not actually stop the application — the Deployment controller creates a new one automatically.

The distinction between a **pod** (ephemeral, changing IP) and a **service** (stable endpoint) is the foundational networking concept in Kubernetes. Every production Kubernetes application relies on this pattern.

Minikube made it possible to practice all of this on a local machine with the exact same `kubectl` commands that work against production clusters on AWS EKS or Google GKE.
